#Bayesian approach
#Given that you have s heads in total, out of n flips, you would like to find a probability distribution for 𝜃 in [0,1], denoted f(𝜃).

#The major philosophy is to assume that f(𝜃) is proportional to the likelihood of data under 𝜃; that is, 
#if a 𝜃 value obtains a likelihood that is greater than or equal to the likelihood of 𝜃, then f(𝜃) should be greater than or equal to f(𝜃). You should thus have:
#f(𝜃) \propto  \displaystyle{n \choose{s}} \𝜃^s (1-\𝜃)^{n-s}
#where $\propto$ denotes 'proportional to', so there exists some constant C that does not depend on 𝜃 so that:
#f(𝜃)  =  \displaystyle C \cdot {n \choose{s}} \theta^s (1- \𝜃)^{n-s}

#Simplifying this using basic linear algebra, the value of f(𝜃) is given by:
#f(\𝜃) = (n+1) {n \choose s} \𝜃^s (1-\𝜃)^{n-s} $$

